---
import '../../styles/global.css';
import LessonLayout from '../../layouts/LessonLayout.astro';
import LessonHeader from '../../components/LessonHeader.astro';
import LessonNav from '../../components/LessonNav.astro';
import InsightBox from '../../components/InsightBox.astro';
import ExerciseBox from '../../components/ExerciseBox.astro';
import Formula from '../../components/Formula.astro';
import TagBadge from '../../components/TagBadge.astro';
import SlopeNudgeDemo from '../../components/demos/SlopeNudgeDemo.astro';
---

<LessonLayout title="Derivatives, Intuitively" lessonNumber="0.3" section="Foundations">

    <LessonHeader lessonNumber="0.3" title="Derivatives, Intuitively" description="A derivative is one number that answers the nudge question from lesson 0.1: wiggle the input a hair, how much does the output move? No heavy calculus — just the few ideas the framework needs.">
        <TagBadge variant="math">math</TagBadge>
        <TagBadge variant="default">11 min read</TagBadge>
    </LessonHeader>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Standing on a hill in the fog.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            You're on a hillside, fog everywhere, can't see a thing. But you can feel the ground under your feet
            tilt. That tilt tells you two things: which way is downhill, and how steep it is. That's a derivative —
            the steepness of a function at the exact spot you're standing.
        </p>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            More precisely: the derivative of a function at a point is <strong>how much the output changes per tiny
            change in the input</strong>. If a small step right makes the output rise twice as fast as the step, the
            derivative is 2. If the output drops, the derivative is negative.
        </p>
        <InsightBox>
            <p class="text-sm">Two pieces of information live in one number. The <strong>sign</strong> says direction
            (does the output go up or down when the input goes up?). The <strong>size</strong> says how fast. Learning
            uses both: sign tells a knob which way to turn, size tells it how hard.</p>
        </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">The nudge definition.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Take a function <span class="font-mono">f</span>. Pick an input <span class="font-mono">x</span>. Add a
            tiny amount <span class="font-mono">&epsilon;</span> (epsilon, think 0.0001). See how much the output moved,
            and divide by the size of the nudge:
        </p>
        <Formula caption="As the nudge ε shrinks toward zero, this ratio settles on the derivative.">
            slope &asymp; ( f(x + &epsilon;) &minus; f(x) ) / &epsilon;
        </Formula>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            That's it. "Output change divided by input change," with the input change made tiny. The exact derivative
            is what this ratio approaches as <span class="font-mono">&epsilon;</span> goes to zero. We write it
            <span class="font-mono">df/dx</span> or <span class="font-mono">f&prime;(x)</span>.
        </p>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Computing the ratio with a small-but-real <span class="font-mono">&epsilon;</span> is called a
            <strong>finite difference</strong>. It's approximate, but it's something you can do with arithmetic alone —
            which makes it the perfect way to <em>check</em> the exact derivatives your framework computes. We'll use
            that trick to prove the engine correct in Unit 2.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">A worked example.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Take <span class="font-mono">f(x) = x&sup2;</span> at <span class="font-mono">x = 3</span>. So
            <span class="font-mono">f(3) = 9</span>. Nudge with <span class="font-mono">&epsilon; = 0.001</span>:
        </p>
        <div class="bg-white border border-mt-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-4 font-mono text-sm">
            f(3.001) = 3.001 &times; 3.001 = 9.006001<br>
            slope &asymp; (9.006001 &minus; 9) / 0.001 = 6.001 &asymp; <strong>6</strong>
        </div>

        <SlopeNudgeDemo />
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The derivative of <span class="font-mono">x&sup2;</span> at 3 is 6. (The exact rule is
            <span class="font-mono">2x</span>, and 2&times;3 = 6 — the finite difference landed right next to it, off
            only by the leftover <span class="font-mono">&epsilon;</span>.) That's the nudge question from lesson 0.1,
            answered with arithmetic.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">The handful of rules we'll actually need.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            This isn't a calculus course. For a scalar engine you only need a few derivative rules, and each one is
            the answer to "if I wiggle the input, how does this operation's output move?"
        </p>
        <div class="bg-white border border-mt-border rounded-xl overflow-hidden mb-4">
            <table class="w-full text-sm">
                <thead><tr class="bg-mt-bg text-left"><th class="px-5 py-2 font-semibold">Operation</th><th class="px-5 py-2 font-semibold">Derivative</th><th class="px-5 py-2 font-semibold">In words</th></tr></thead>
                <tbody class="divide-y divide-mt-border font-mono text-xs">
                    <tr><td class="px-5 py-2">c (a constant)</td><td class="px-5 py-2">0</td><td class="px-5 py-2 font-sans text-mt-muted">a constant never moves</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="px-5 py-2">x</td><td class="px-5 py-2">1</td><td class="px-5 py-2 font-sans text-mt-muted">moves exactly as fast as itself</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="px-5 py-2">x&sup2;</td><td class="px-5 py-2">2x</td><td class="px-5 py-2 font-sans text-mt-muted">steeper the further out you are</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="px-5 py-2">c &times; x</td><td class="px-5 py-2">c</td><td class="px-5 py-2 font-sans text-mt-muted">scaling the input scales the slope</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="px-5 py-2">f + g</td><td class="px-5 py-2">f&prime; + g&prime;</td><td class="px-5 py-2 font-sans text-mt-muted">slopes of a sum just add</td></tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed">
            The one rule left — how to handle a function <em>inside</em> a function — is the chain rule, and it's big
            enough to get its own lesson (0.5). With these plus the chain rule, you can differentiate everything a
            small neural net needs.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <ExerciseBox title="Try it by hand">
            <p class="text-sm text-mt-muted">Estimate the slope of <span class="font-mono">f(x) = x&sup2;</span> at
            <span class="font-mono">x = 2</span> using a nudge of <span class="font-mono">&epsilon; = 0.001</span>.
            Compute <span class="font-mono">f(2.001)</span>, subtract <span class="font-mono">f(2)</span>, divide by
            0.001. You should land right next to 4 (because the rule <span class="font-mono">2x</span> gives 2&times;2 = 4).</p>
        </ExerciseBox>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Key takeaways</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">1</span></div><p class="text-sm">A derivative is output-change per tiny input-change: which way the output moves, and how fast.</p></div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">2</span></div><p class="text-sm">You can estimate one with arithmetic (a finite difference) — which is how we'll later check the framework's exact answers.</p></div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">3</span></div><p class="text-sm">A scalar engine needs only a few derivative rules plus the chain rule. That's the whole math toolkit.</p></div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <LessonNav
        prevHref="/foundations/learning-as-fitting" prevLabel="Prev: Learning Is Fitting"
        nextHref="/foundations/gradients" nextLabel="Next: Gradients"
    />

</LessonLayout>
